t makes total sense that the federal government lacked a state church now. The founders were from completely different Christian and deist backgrounds so a federal church would have just recreated a lot of the sectarian issues Europe dealt with. They weren't some far reaching 21st century secularists. ", "author": "HorrorGameDev", "created": 1770613504629, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Smurfection", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "I was never taught 9 of the original 13 states had Christian state religions. The wall of separation argument is completely fabricated.", "last_comment_created": 1770636442593, "content": "<p>Twelve of the thirteen original states had religious requirements for voting and serving office.</p>\n<p>This pretty much validates the Ten Commandments existing in classrooms and school prayer. Massachusetts still had  a formal state religion until the 1840s. That's three generations of Americans living in a commonwealth with a state church.</p>\n<p>It makes total sense that the federal government lacked a state church now. The founders were from completely different Christian and deist backgrounds so a federal church would have just recreated a lot of the sectarian issues Europe dealt with. They weren't some far reaching 21st century secularists.</p>\n", "score_down": 2, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 17, "score_up": 64, "is_edited": true, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "2020677805915144420", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_